1.c: poor housing. Lower class occupants. Adjacent to Malden City Dump.
1.b: good transportation, schools, etc. Near employment.

areaDesc.5: Foreclosures were heavy in this area with the bulk of the overhand still held by banks. The neighborhood has been largely Jewish for some time with lower class Jews moving into the section at present.

1.c: obsolescence. Lower class populace. Poor housing.
1.b: good transportation, schools, etc. Strong Catholic influence with parochial schools.

areaDesc.5: Negro is concentrated around Sherman St. This neighborhood was heavily vacant until summer of 1937 - since then vacancy has decreased considerably.

1.b: fairly desirable residential neighborhood. Good transportation, schools, etc. Property is very well held.

areaDesc.5: Mortgage lenders will grant better terms on single houses than on two family units. There is a tendency for less desirable occupants from Everett to move into this area.

1.b: Fairly desirable section of older houses which are very well held. Good transportation, schools, etc.

areaDesc.5: Few properties in this neighborhood have changed hands in recent years. The 2 family units are principally concentrated south of Pleasant St., and owner occupancy is very heavy in this portion of the area with pride of ownership prevalent throughout. Ripley, Edmund, Clinton and Vernon Streets are below par of the section.

1.b: fairly desirable section of modest homes. Good transportation, schools, etc.

areaDesc.5: The eastern end of the section becomes poorer gradually and financing is difficult to obtain. Less desirables encroaching slowly.
